Read/Load an image¶

There are several ways to read an image from disk, ie. libraries to do that. For instance, the main one are:

opencv¶

import cv2
from skimage.data import chelsea
from matplotlib.pyplot import imshow, axis
%matplotlib inline

im = chelsea()

im_path = "/tmp/chelsea.jpg"

cv2.imwrite(im_path, im)

loaded_im = cv2.imread(im_path)

imshow(loaded_im)
axis("off")

(-0.5, 450.5, 299.5, -0.5)

skimage¶

from skimage.data import chelsea
from skimage.io import imread, imsave
from matplotlib.pyplot import imshow, axis, subplot
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
%matplotlib inline

im = chelsea()

im_path = "/tmp/chelsea.jpg"

imsave(im_path, im)

loaded_im = imread(im_path)

imshow(loaded_im)
axis("off")

(-0.5, 450.5, 299.5, -0.5)

numpy¶

from skimage.data import chelsea
import numpy as np
from matplotlib.pyplot import imshow, axis, subplot
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
%matplotlib inline

im = chelsea()

im_path = "/tmp/chelsea.npy"

np.save(im_path, im)

loaded_im = np.load(im_path)

imshow(loaded_im)
axis("off")

(-0.5, 450.5, 299.5, -0.5)

load_img(path:Path, img_format:ImageFormat)

save_img[source]

save_img(arr:ndarray, path:Path, img_format:ImageFormat)

for img_format, ext in zip([ImageFormat.NUMPY, ImageFormat.OPENCV, ImageFormat.SKIMAGE], ["npy", "jpg", "jpg"]):
    
    im_path = "/tmp/chelsea.{}".format(ext)
    
    im = chelsea()

    save_img(im, Path(im_path), img_format)

    loaded_im = load_img(Path(im_path), img_format=img_format)

    imshow(loaded_im)
    axis("off")

Image processing ops¶

rescale_intensity¶

There are some operations usual in image intensity. Rescaling an intensity from one range to another is a classical one. Mostly used, for converting any image to 8bit image.

from skimage.exposure import rescale_intensity
import numpy as np
im = chelsea()
subplot(1,2,1)
imshow(rescale_intensity(loaded_im, in_range="image", out_range=np.uint8))
axis("off")
subplot(1,2,2)
imshow(rescale_intensity(loaded_im, in_range=(0,128), out_range=np.uint8))
axis("off")

(-0.5, 450.5, 299.5, -0.5)
